# Typography: No Em-Dashes

Never use em-dashes (`—`, U+2014) in user-facing copy, JSX/HTML, JSON-LD, metadata, code comments, commit messages, or PR descriptions.

Always use a plain ASCII hyphen-minus (`-`, U+002D) instead. This applies to all files in the project, including but not limited to `.tsx`, `.ts`, `.jsx`, `.js`, `.md`, `.mdx`, `.json`, and `.html`.

## Examples

```tsx
// BAD - uses em-dash
<p>State-of-the-art facilities — built for scale.</p>

// GOOD - uses plain hyphen
<p>State-of-the-art facilities - built for scale.</p>
```

## When Producing or Editing Copy

- If new copy needs a separator/break, use ` - ` (space hyphen space) or restructure with commas/periods.
- When pasting content from another source (Word, Google Docs, etc.), replace any `—` with `-` before saving.
- The same applies to other "smart" dash characters when used as em-dash replacements (e.g., en-dash `–` U+2013): prefer `-` unless the user explicitly asks to preserve them.
